--- Jeff Tickner <JeffT(-at-)softlanding.com> wrote:
> 
> I picked up a new 78 bus this Saturday from another
> list member. I
> purchased this bus the way everybody says (from
> experience) NOT to. Went to
> look at it as it was supposed to be a good body for
> the northeast and
> unknown mechanicals. 8 passenger layout, really nice
> interior, body has
> some rust repair, a bad paint job and then surface
> rust. Some rust on the
> front beam. Battery tray badly repaired. 80K on the
> odometer but no one is
> sure if that's right. The tires are TOAST, can't
> believe they hold air. The
> exhaust is strangely pristine except for the
> muffler, everything is really
> nice, the cool tin under the push rod tubes is in
> place.
> 
> The engine was a complete unknown. There is no
> engine seal which should be
> a warning that it may have overheated. The current
> seller had purchased it
> in non-running condition with some bizarre
> instructions about sticking a
> piece of wood into one of the exposed relays on the
> double relay and there
> was some mysterious "extra" wiring on the harness
> near the double relay
> plugs. He replaced the double relay and it still
> didn't work, so he puts it
> up for sale. So I buy it. No compression test, no
> road test etc etc. Pay
> too much for it, but the seller knows I'm hooked
> (maybe I have a goofy grin
> on my face?)
> 
> So essentially I had just paid $1000 for a bus that
> would be free on the
> west coast. It might have a blown engine, bad
> tranny, bad brakes etc etc
> etc. I have a spare engine, tranny, complete FI
> system as spares for my 78
> camper, but potential for a lot of labor. On the
> plus side the owner tossed
> in a tow bar and sourced a $100 replacement front
> beam for me that turned
> out to be an awesome adjustable with trailing arms,
> drag link, KYBs and
> brake rotors all attached. I put some plates on it
> and AAA tows it home for
> me.
> 
> Sunday afternoon I finally had time to look at it.
> Get out my VW FI trouble
> shooting guide and start with the double relay, test
> the double relay in my
> other 78, works fine. Pull the extra wiring off, no
> power. Look around and
> notice that the wire to the coil is pulled off, in
> fact the coil doesn't
> have the extra push-on connectors for it. Swap coils
> for a known good,
> connect the wire, replace the fuse. Pump now works
> when I push the AFM
> flap. I crank it and no start. So I check the points
> and they are fried.
> Get my spare set of points in there, set the gap
> with a feeler and it
> starts roughly. Get my wife (I can't wait till my
> kids are old enough to
> turn the key for me, but at age 2 and 3.5 they
> aren't yet) to crank it, set
> the dwell with my new $10 dwell meter (thanks to the
> guy that posted that
> to the list) and it runs like a top. I checked the
> timing and what I saw
> while my cheapo timing light chose to work looked
> within a few degrees of
> correct. Still have to do a compression test to see
> what kind of shape the
> engine is in.
> 
> The bus has a short on the right side that is
> blowing fuses when I use the
> hazards or turn signals, the alternator light comes
> on when I rev it so
> still some stuff to work out. Additional finds, a
> very nice 6 ply spare
> under the cover in the rear, have to inflate it hard
> to see if it's dry
> rotted. A gas heater that is missing it's fuel pump
> (the T is gone out of
> the fuel line) but the combuster fan comes on when
> you turn the knob. I
> have 2 other gas heaters for spares so I might
> actually get this one
> working. have to go through and replace fuel lines,
> filler neck and vent
> lines. The charcoal cannister was removed but is in
> 1 of the boxes of parts
> that came with the bus.
> 
> This bus is also getting a very high approval rating
> from the wife and
> kids. I'm loking forward to a happy bus and hoping
> my camper doesn't get
> jealous and start throwing fits ;-)
> 
> Jeff Tickner
> 78 Camper "10C JED"
> 78 8 passenger "Great Pumpkin"
> 2000 Golf GLS TDI
> 
